Test module for `crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/run/`, covering `wait_for_relay_snippet` and the interactive `setsid --ctty` controlling-terminal fix (ADR-048); `proxy_diagnostic` tests live in the sibling `diagnostic` submodule instead.

Two tests exercise the relay-wait race using real subprocesses and a pid-derived port (`test_port`) to avoid collisions across parallel `cargo test` runs: `waits_out_a_delayed_relay_bind_then_proceeds` spawns a listener that binds after a 300ms delay and asserts the probe neither returns instantly nor rides out the full 5s timeout. `never_opens_a_connection_to_the_listener` is a regression guard — the probe must use `/proc/net/tcp` and never actually `accept()` a TCP connection, since real `socat ...,fork` relays forward such probe connections straight into the host proxy, producing spurious "EOF before request head" errors.

The remaining tests validate the `setsid --ctty` fix via real PTYs (`nix::pty::openpty`), not mocks. `stat_probe_script` parses `/proc/self/stat` fields (pid, pgrp, session, tty_nr, tpgid) using a `read` builtin redirect specifically so `/proc/self` resolves to the shell itself rather than a `cat` subprocess — using `$(cat …)` here would break the test. `run_on_private_pty` wires a PTY slave as stdin/stdout/stderr, mirroring the exact stdio shape `pty::run_on_pty` gives the caged process. `assert_leader_on_ctty` checks the process is a session leader (SID==PID), its own pgrp, and foreground pgrp of its ctty (TPGID==PGRP, not -1). `setsid_ctty_makes_the_pty_the_controlling_terminal` confirms `setsid --ctty --wait` achieves this state while a bare `sh -c` launch does not — this is the load-bearing distinction, since without it, caged Node processes busy-spin at 100% CPU via `tcgetpgrp`/ENOTTY under `--unshare-pid`.